{%- doc -%}
  Kitchero document-head meta bundle.

  Emits (in this order): a single Liquid dispatch block that resolves
  share title / share url / share image / share description / OG type /
  Twitter card variant based on the current template; OpenGraph basics,
  an OG price pair on product pages, OG locale pair for multi-language
  shops, Twitter card tags (card variant adapts to whether a share image
  exists), a reading-list block (`application/ld+json`) for `product` and
  `article` templates powered by the native `| structured_data` filter,
  and finally Apple mobile-app hints.

  Consumer: only `layout/theme.liquid` (one render site). Do not render
  from sections — the document head is the single allowed context.

  Architecture: single `case` dispatch over `request.page_type`, named
  helper assigns for share values, `| structured_data` filter for JSON-LD,
  Twitter card variant selector keyed off share-image presence, and a
  fallback share-image pipeline that prefers page_image → shop.brand.logo.
{%- enddoc -%}

{%- liquid
  # ── Share attributes (OG + Twitter share the same resolved values) ──
  assign share_title = page_title | default: shop.name
  assign share_description = page_description | default: shop.description | default: shop.name
  assign share_url = canonical_url | default: request.origin
  assign share_image = page_image
  # Merchant-uploaded default social-share image (1200×630 recommended).
  # Sits between page_image (template-specific) and shop.brand.logo
  # (usually square and ugly when cropped into a 1.91:1 social card).
  # Home/collection/page/search links paste into Slack/FB/LinkedIn with
  # a purpose-built preview instead of a zoomed-in logo.
  if share_image == blank and settings.kt_default_share_image != blank
    assign share_image = settings.kt_default_share_image
  endif
  if share_image == blank and shop.brand.logo != blank
    assign share_image = shop.brand.logo
  endif
  # Video featured_media guard — product.featured_media can be a video
  # object when the merchant's first media slot is a YouTube/Vimeo embed
  # or uploaded .mp4. In that case share_image.width / .height resolve
  # to 0 or nil, which breaks the og:image:width / og:image:height pair
  # below (emits width="0" and spec validators reject the card). Fall
  # back to the merchant default or logo so every page has a usable image.
  if share_image != blank and share_image.width == 0
    if settings.kt_default_share_image != blank
      assign share_image = settings.kt_default_share_image
    elsif shop.brand.logo != blank
      assign share_image = shop.brand.logo
    else
      assign share_image = blank
    endif
  endif

  # ── Template dispatch (case over request.page_type; each branch sets
  # only what differs from the website default). ──
  assign og_type = 'website'
  case request.page_type
    when 'product'
      assign og_type = 'product'
    when 'article'
      assign og_type = 'article'
    when 'password'
      assign share_url = request.origin
    when 'collection'
      assign og_type = 'website'
    when '404'
      assign og_type = 'website'
  endcase

  # ── Twitter card variant: only upgrade to large-image when we actually
  # have an image to show. Avoids an empty-looking large card. ──
  if share_image != blank
    assign twitter_card = 'summary_large_image'
  else
    assign twitter_card = 'summary'
  endif

  # ── Twitter handle: strip the domain from the twitter_link setting and
  # prepend "@" so admins can paste the full profile URL. `remove_first: '@'`
  # protects against the admin pasting a bare handle like "@yourshop" (or
  # an X URL containing "@") — without it the prepend would double to "@@".
  assign twitter_handle = ''
  if settings.kt_social_twitter != blank
    assign twitter_handle = settings.kt_social_twitter | split: 'twitter.com/' | last | split: 'x.com/' | last | remove: '/' | remove_first: '@' | prepend: '@'
  endif

  # ── Share-image sizing ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  # Facebook/LinkedIn/Slack all score and lay out share cards against a
  # 1200 px-wide reference (the official OG recommendation is 1200×630).
  # Previously we emitted the raw source URL with whatever dimensions
  # the merchant happened to upload, which on tiny logo images looks
  # like a broken thumbnail and on huge product hero shots forces every
  # scraper to pull several MB. We cap the request at 1200 via
  # `image_url: width: 1200` so Shopify's CDN resizes on our behalf,
  # then compute a matching height so og:image:width/height stay
  # consistent with the pixels the scraper actually downloads. For
  # source images narrower than 1200 we pass the native width through
  # unchanged — `image_url` never upscales, so lying about the width
  # would mismatch the scraper's actual download.
  if share_image != blank
    if share_image.width >= 1200
      assign og_image_width = 1200
      assign og_image_height = share_image.height | times: 1200 | divided_by: share_image.width
    else
      assign og_image_width = share_image.width
      assign og_image_height = share_image.height
    endif
  endif
-%}

{%- comment -%}
  ─── Robots ───
  Search results, 404s, and every customer-account page are not
  meant to be indexed by Google. Shopify's default robots.txt covers
  /account + /search at the path level, but Search Console can still
  surface these URLs if they're linked from elsewhere — the meta tag
  belt-and-braces the robots exclusion at the document level so bots
  that honour meta-robots (Googlebot, Bingbot, etc.) drop the page
  from the index regardless of path.

  We match on `request.page_type` rather than `template.name`
  because page_type is stable across template suffixes
  (customers/login.suffix vs customers/login).
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- comment -%}
  Extended list:
  - `captcha` — Shopify's robot-challenge interstitial. Never user
    content, always noindex.
  - `gift_card` — the issued-gift-card landing page URLs
    (/gift_cards/<id>/<code>) contain the redemption code in the
    path. Google must NEVER index these — a leaked URL becomes an
    open redemption exposure. MUST noindex.
  - Other customer/* pages + search + 404 carried over from the
    previous list.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- assign hidden_page_types = 'search,404,captcha,gift_card,password,cart,policy,customers/login,customers/register,customers/account,customers/addresses,customers/order,customers/reset_password,customers/activate_account' | split: ',' -%}
{%- if hidden_page_types contains request.page_type -%}
  <meta name="robots" content="noindex">
{%- comment -%}
  Faceted collection / search URLs (`?filter.v.option.color=red`,
  `?filter.p.tag=...`, `?q=` on collections) generate a high-
  cardinality URL space — without `noindex,follow` Google indexes
  thousands of filter permutations, dilutes the parent collection's
  link equity, and Search Console shows the parent dropping out of
  the top results. `follow` keeps the linked products themselves
  crawlable so the discovery path stays intact. Mirrors what
  premium peer themes (and the Shopify Online Store team) recommend.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- elsif request.path contains '/collections/' and request.query_string contains 'filter.' -%}
  <meta name="robots" content="noindex,follow">
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%}
  ─── OpenGraph ───

  `og:locale` per OpenGraph spec must be in `xx_YY` format (lang +
  region). Shopify's `request.locale.iso_code` returns just the
  language code for the 5 enabled locales (en, tr, de, fr, es) —
  the `replace: '-', '_'` is a no-op on these. Without a region
  pair, Facebook / LinkedIn / Slack OG previews silently fall back
  to en_US and Theme Store reviewers flag it as "invalid og:locale
  format". The case map below picks the most common region per
  language; merchants targeting a different region (e.g. en_GB
  rather than en_US) can override later via metafields.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- liquid
  case request.locale.iso_code
    when 'en'
      assign og_locale = 'en_US'
    when 'tr'
      assign og_locale = 'tr_TR'
    when 'de'
      assign og_locale = 'de_DE'
    when 'fr'
      assign og_locale = 'fr_FR'
    when 'es'
      assign og_locale = 'es_ES'
    else
      assign og_locale = request.locale.iso_code | replace: '-', '_'
  endcase
-%}
<meta property="og:site_name" content="{{ shop.name | escape }}">
<meta property="og:title" content="{{ share_title | escape }}">
<meta property="og:description" content="{{ share_description | escape }}">
<meta property="og:url" content="{{ share_url | escape }}">
<meta property="og:type" content="{{ og_type }}">
<meta property="og:locale" content="{{ og_locale }}">

{%- if shop.published_locales.size > 1 -%}
  {%- for locale in shop.published_locales -%}
    {%- unless locale.iso_code == request.locale.iso_code -%}
      {%- liquid
        case locale.iso_code
          when 'en'
            assign alt_locale = 'en_US'
          when 'tr'
            assign alt_locale = 'tr_TR'
          when 'de'
            assign alt_locale = 'de_DE'
          when 'fr'
            assign alt_locale = 'fr_FR'
          when 'es'
            assign alt_locale = 'es_ES'
          else
            assign alt_locale = locale.iso_code | replace: '-', '_'
        endcase
      -%}
      <meta property="og:locale:alternate" content="{{ alt_locale }}">
    {%- endunless -%}
  {%- endfor -%}
{%- endif -%}

{%- if share_image != blank -%}
  {%- comment -%}
    Emit both og:image and og:image:secure_url as https. Old Facebook
    scrapers preferred protocol-relative http:, but modern scrapers
    (FB/LinkedIn/Slack/Twitter/Discord) all honour https: and a handful
    now reject mixed-content references from https origins. Having
    og:image itself be http caused "not secure" warnings in Slack's
    link preview renderer.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <meta property="og:image" content="https:{{ share_image | image_url: width: og_image_width }}">
  <meta property="og:image:secure_url" content="https:{{ share_image | image_url: width: og_image_width }}">
  <meta property="og:image:width" content="{{ og_image_width }}">
  <meta property="og:image:height" content="{{ og_image_height }}">
  <meta property="og:image:alt" content="{{ share_title | escape }}">
{%- endif -%}

{%- if request.page_type == 'product' and product -%}
  {%- comment -%}
    FB Commerce Catalog ingests `product:price:amount` as a dotted
    decimal. `money_without_currency` renders locale-specific
    separators (e.g. "99,00" in French stores) which Facebook's feed
    parser rejects. Divide cents by 100.0 to guarantee a
    locale-independent "99.00". `round: 2` keeps two decimals.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- comment -%}
    og:price:amount is product.price (cents) divided by 100, which is
    always denominated in the SHOP's primary currency — not the buyer's
    market currency. Earlier this snippet emitted og:price:currency from
    cart.currency.iso_code (buyer's currency under Markets), so a UK
    shopper visiting a USD-primary store published `og:price:amount=99.00`
    tagged with `og:price:currency=GBP` — a 28% mis-priced FB catalog
    feed. Pin currency to the shop primary so amount+currency stay in the
    same denomination.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- assign og_price_decimal = product.price | divided_by: 100.0 | round: 2 -%}
  <meta property="og:price:amount" content="{{ og_price_decimal }}">
  <meta property="og:price:currency" content="{{ shop.currency.iso_code }}">
  {%- comment -%}
    Emit both the modern product:availability key AND the legacy
    og:availability key — FB Business and some product-catalog
    scrapers still expect og:availability with "instock"/"oos" form.
    product:brand + product:retailer_item_id (SKU) are required by
    Facebook Catalog / Shop feed ingestion. product:condition is a
    required FB catalog field; default to "new" — merchants selling
    refurbished/used can override via a future metafield.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <meta property="product:availability" content="{% if product.available %}in stock{% else %}out of stock{% endif %}">
  <meta property="og:availability" content="{% if product.available %}instock{% else %}oos{% endif %}">
  <meta property="product:condition" content="new">
  {%- if product.vendor != blank -%}
    <meta property="product:brand" content="{{ product.vendor | escape }}">
  {%- endif -%}
  {%- assign active_variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant -%}
  {%- if active_variant.sku != blank -%}
    <meta property="product:retailer_item_id" content="{{ active_variant.sku | escape }}">
  {%- endif -%}
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%}
  Blog RSS/Atom link — lets RSS readers, podcast catchers, and
  Google Discover's feed backbone discover the blog's feed. Shopify
  auto-generates /<blog>.atom from every blog's articles. Gate on
  `blog` page-type so we only emit the link on blog / article pages
  where the `blog` object is populated.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- if request.page_type == 'blog' or request.page_type == 'article' -%}
  {%- if blog != blank -%}
    <link rel="alternate" type="application/atom+xml" title="{{ blog.title | escape }}" href="{{ blog.url }}.atom">
  {%- endif -%}
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%}
  Article meta for FB/LinkedIn article share cards + social-graph
  indexing. The modern `article:*` namespace is scraped by both
  Facebook and LinkedIn; Twitter doesn't use them but does no harm.
  Gate on `article` to avoid emitting on non-article pages.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- if request.page_type == 'article' and article -%}
  <meta property="article:published_time" content="{{ article.published_at | date: '%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S%z' }}">
  <meta property="article:modified_time" content="{{ article.updated_at | date: '%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S%z' }}">
  {%- if article.author != blank -%}
    <meta property="article:author" content="{{ article.author | escape }}">
  {%- endif -%}
  {%- if blog.title != blank -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Facebook's article scraper reads article:section to categorize
      the content in Open Graph news aggregation. blog.title is the
      closest section analogue — e.g. "News", "Journal", "Design Tips".
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <meta property="article:section" content="{{ blog.title | escape }}">
  {%- endif -%}
  {%- for tag in article.tags -%}
    <meta property="article:tag" content="{{ tag | escape }}">
  {%- endfor -%}
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%} ─── Twitter ─── {%- endcomment -%}
<meta name="twitter:card" content="{{ twitter_card }}">
<meta name="twitter:title" content="{{ share_title | escape }}">
<meta name="twitter:description" content="{{ share_description | escape }}">
{%- if twitter_handle != blank -%}
  <meta name="twitter:site" content="{{ twitter_handle }}">
  <meta name="twitter:creator" content="{{ twitter_handle }}">
{%- endif -%}
{%- if share_image != blank -%}
  <meta name="twitter:image" content="https:{{ share_image | image_url: width: og_image_width }}">
  <meta name="twitter:image:width" content="{{ og_image_width }}">
  <meta name="twitter:image:height" content="{{ og_image_height }}">
  <meta name="twitter:image:alt" content="{{ share_title | escape }}">
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%} ─── Structured data (product + article) via native filter ─── {%- endcomment -%}
{%- if request.page_type == 'product' and product -%}
  <script type="application/ld+json">{{ product | structured_data }}</script>
  {%- comment -%}
    aggregateRating supplement — Shopify's native `| structured_data`
    filter emits Product with price/availability/SKU/image but does
    NOT automatically pull `product.metafields.reviews.rating` into
    schema. The theme DOES render stars on the PDP reading that
    metafield, so Google's Rich Results Test flags "Review snippets
    not present" — visible UI, absent schema. Emit a supplementary
    Product block with matching @id (the canonical URL Shopify uses);
    Google merges multiple same-@id Product schemas per spec.
    Gated on the metafield existing — new stores without reviews
    installed get nothing extra.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- assign sd_rating = product.metafields.reviews.rating.value.rating | default: product.metafields.custom.rating.value -%}
  {%- assign sd_rating_count = product.metafields.reviews.rating_count.value -%}
  {%- assign sd_rating_scale = product.metafields.reviews.rating.value.scale_max | default: 5 -%}
  {%- if sd_rating and sd_rating_count and sd_rating_count > 0 -%}
    <script type="application/ld+json">
      {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "Product",
        "@id": {{ canonical_url | json }},
        "aggregateRating": {
          "@type": "AggregateRating",
          "ratingValue": {{ sd_rating | json }},
          "bestRating": {{ sd_rating_scale | json }},
          "worstRating": "1",
          "reviewCount": {{ sd_rating_count | json }}
        }
      }
    </script>
  {%- endif -%}
{%- elsif request.page_type == 'article' and article -%}
  <script type="application/ld+json">{{ article | structured_data }}</script>
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%}
  Mobile-app hints.

  `mobile-web-app-capable` is the modern, cross-browser equivalent;
  `apple-mobile-web-app-capable` is Safari's older form, deprecation-
  warned by Chrome 111+. Emitting both keeps iOS home-screen saves
  working while silencing Chrome DevTools' deprecation warning.
{%- endcomment -%}
<meta name="mobile-web-app-capable" content="yes">
<meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-capable" content="yes">
<meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-title" content="{{ shop.name | escape }}">
<meta name="format-detection" content="telephone=no">
